{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524182"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:02:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:02:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13978"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13978"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.01,0.39,0.55,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6612"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107405"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6612"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13978"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89885"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"527"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1769"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13378"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33969"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39999"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44557"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107405"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of right iliac fossa pain. He reports worsening symptoms over the past few days, including fever and back pain. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a palpable mass in the right iliac fossa. There is pain on extension of the right thigh. A CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diverticulitis","Crohn\u0027s disease","Perforated appendicitis","Primary psoas abscess","Pyelonephritis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and CT findings in this case are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eperforated appendicitis\u003C/strong\u003E complicated by abscess formation - from a localised perforation. The CT shows a large abscess cavity (fluid-filled with pockets of gas) in the right iliac fossa. The patient\u0027s two-week history of right iliac fossa pain, worsening symptoms with fever, and the presence of a palpable mass are typical features of a perforated appendix with abscess formation. The pain on extension of the right thigh (psoas sign) suggests involvement of the psoas muscle, which can occur when an appendiceal abscess extends posteriorly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn the CT adjacent to the appendix, there is a clearly defined collection containing fluid and gas, consistent with a periappendiceal abscess secondary to perforated appendicitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E can present with right iliac fossa pain and abscess formation. However, the acute onset in a previously well patient without a history of gastrointestinal symptoms makes this diagnosis less likely. Crohn\u0027s disease typically has a more insidious onset with chronic symptoms such as diarrhoea, weight loss, and recurrent abdominal pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary psoas abscess\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by haematogenous spread of bacteria, is a possibility but is less common than a secondary abscess due to direct spread of infection by appendicitis. Primary psoas abscesses are often associated with immunocompromised state or intravenous drug use, which are not mentioned in this patient\u0027s history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyelonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause flank pain and fever but typically presents with urinary symptoms such as dysuria and frequency. The presence of a palpable mass in the right iliac fossa is not characteristic of uncomplicated pyelonephritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiverticulitis\u003C/strong\u003E is included as an additional differential diagnosis. While it can cause abdominal pain and abscess formation, it typically affects the left side of the colon. Right-sided diverticulitis is possible but less common, especially in Western populations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn cases of suspected complicated appendicitis, CT imaging is crucial for confirming the diagnosis and identifying complications such as abscess formation. Management typically involves antibiotics and percutaneous drainage of the abscess, followed by interval appendectomy once the inflammation has subsided. In some cases, immediate surgical intervention may be necessary, depending on the patient\u0027s clinical condition and the extent of the abscess - in the case the patient underwent a right hemicolectomy and abscess drainage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Perforated appendicitis can lead to secondary psoas abscess formation, presenting with right iliac fossa pain, fever, and pain on hip extension.","CT imaging is crucial for diagnosing complicated appendicitis and associated abscesses.","Differential diagnoses for right iliac fossa abscesses include Crohn\u0027s disease, primary psoas abscess, and pyelonephritis."],"references":["Zhou S, Cheng Y, Cheng N, et al. Early versus delayed appendicectomy for appendiceal phlegmon or abscess. Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews. Available at: https://www.cochranelibrary.com/cdsr/doi/10.1002/14651858.CD011670.pub3/full","Goel A, Murphy A, Amer M, et al. Appendicular abscess. In: Radiopaedia.org [online]. 2024. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/appendicular-abscess"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89885"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13978"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20871"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20871"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Kk68oxRRq2McpW6Te2SVd2Wr0FuOX4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Kk68oxRRq2McpW6Te2SVd2Wr0FuOX4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":405,"height":495}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89885"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-29T20:42:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-29T20:43:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6612"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107405"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":